He is the son of [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto]] and [[Kushinadahime]].<ref name="Shinto">{{Cite web |date=2007-09-30 |title=Encyclopedia of Shinto - Home : Kami in Classic Texts : Yashimajinumi |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930182726/http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=181 |access-date=2023-11-13 |website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Mori |first=Mizue |title=Yashimajinumi |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9724 |website=[[Kokugakuin University]] Encyclopedia of Shinto}}</ref> and father of {{ill|Fuha-no-Mojikunusunu|ja|布波能母遅久奴須奴神}}<ref name=":2">{{cite book |last=Herbert |first=J. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sg_JBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT402 |title=Shinto: At the Fountainhead of Japan |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-136-90376-2 |series=Routledge Library Editions: Japan |page=402 |access-date=2020-11-21}}</ref> and husband of {{Interlanguage link|Konohanachiruhime|ja|木花知流比売}}.<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name=":1" />

He is part of the long line from [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto]] to [[Ōkuninushi]].<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name=":1" />

He has other names in the Nihongi. These include Suga no yuyamanushi mina samoruhiko yashimajino and Suga no yuina saka karuhiko yashimade no mikoto..<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name=":1" />

== Origin and Lineage ==
He is the son of [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto]] and [[Kushinadahime]].<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name=":1" />  He appears in the [[Kojiki]], an old Japanese text. He is the first in a line of seventeen generations from Susanoo. The [[Nihon Shoki|Nihongi]] has a different version of his lineage. It places [[Ōkuninushi]] as his descendant in the fifth generation. The Kojiki says Ōkuninushi is in the sixth generation. Yashimajinumi married Ōyamatsumi's daughter, {{Interlanguage link|Konohanachiruhime|ja|木花知流比売}}. This marriage links him to Ōkuninushi..<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name=":1" />

== Significance ==
Yashimajinumi's role is important in Japanese mythology. He connects various deities in these stories. His family ties show the relationships among the gods in ancient texts..<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name=":1" />

