'''Yashimajinumi''' (八島士奴美神) was a Japanese god.<ref name="history">{{cite web |title=Yashimajinumi • . A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史 |url=https://historyofjapan.co.uk/wiki/yashimajinumi/ |access-date=2023-04-27 |website=. A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史 |language=en-GB}}</ref>

His name "Mighty Master Ruling Eightfold Isles" implies he ruled over all of Japan.<ref name="history" /><ref name="Herbert-2010" />{{rp|227}}

He is the son of [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto]] and [[Kushinadahime]].<ref name="Shinto">{{Cite web |date=2007-09-30 |title=Encyclopedia of Shinto - Home : Kami in Classic Texts : Yashimajinumi |url=http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=181 |access-date=2023-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930182726/http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=181 |archive-date=2007-09-30 }}</ref><ref name="Mori">{{Cite web |last=Mori |first=Mizue |title=Yashimajinumi |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9724 |website=[[Kokugakuin University]] Encyclopedia of Shinto}}</ref> and father of {{ill|Fuha-no-Mojikunusunu|ja|布波能母遅久奴須奴神|1=Fuha-no-Mojikunusunu|1=Fuha-no-Mojikunusunu|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fuha-no-Mojikunusunu|13=User:Immanuelle/Fuha-no-Mojikunusunu|qq=}}<ref name="Herbert-2010">{{cite book |last=Herbert |first=J. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sg_JBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT402 |title=Shinto: At the Fountainhead of Japan |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-136-90376-2 |series=Routledge Library Editions: Japan |page=402 |access-date=2020-11-21}}</ref>{{rp|278}} and husband of [[Konohanachiru-hime]].<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name="Mori" />

He is part of the long line from [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto]] to [[Ōkuninushi]].<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name="Mori" />

He has other names in the Nihongi. These include Suga no yuyamanushi mina samoruhiko yashimajino and Suga no yuina saka karuhiko yashimade no mikoto.<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name="Mori" />

== Origin and Lineage ==
He is the son of [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto]] and [[Kushinadahime]].<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name="Mori" /> He appears in the [[Kojiki]], an old Japanese text. He is the first in a line of seventeen generations from Susanoo. The [[Nihon Shoki|Nihongi]] has a different version of his lineage. It places [[Ōkuninushi]] as his descendant in the fifth generation. The Kojiki says Ōkuninushi is in the sixth generation. Yashimajinumi married Ōyamatsumi's daughter, [[Konohanachiru-hime]]. This marriage links him to Ōkuninushi.<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name="Mori" />

== Significance ==
Yashimajinumi's role is important in Japanese mythology. He connects various deities in these stories. His family ties show the relationships among the gods in ancient texts..<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name="Mori" />

==Shrines==
He is worshipped at [[Yasaka Shrine]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 April 2005 |title=Mikogami |url=http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930212535/http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=13 |archive-date=2007-09-30 |access-date=29 September 2019 |website=Encyclopedia of Shinto}}</ref>

