== Significance ==
Yashimajinumi's role is important in Japanese mythology. He connects various deities in these stories. His family ties show the relationships among the gods in ancient texts..<ref name="Shinto" /><ref name="Mori" />

==Shrines==
He is worshipped at [[Yasaka Shrine]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 April 2005 |title=Mikogami |url=http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930212535/http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=13 |archive-date=2007-09-30 |access-date=29 September 2019 |website=Encyclopedia of Shinto}}</ref>

[[Suga Shrine]], claims to stand on the site of the palace Shinto deity [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto|Susanoo]] built after defeating the [[:en:Yamata no Orochi|Yamata no Orochi]], enshrines [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto|Susanoo]], [[Kushinadahime]], and their son Yashimajinumi.<ref>{{cite web |title=第十六番 須我神社 |url=https://shinbutsu.jp/shrines-temples/sugajinja/ |access-date=2020-03-30 |website=出雲國神仏霊場を巡る旅 (Izumo-no-kuni shinbutsu reijo o meguru tabi) |publisher=社寺縁座の会 (Shaji Enza no Kai)}}</ref>

